\begin_layout Subsubsection*
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Sherman Morrison Identity
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Sherman–Morrison–Woodbury Matrix Inversion Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following identities see wide application in factor models, as well
 as in statistics and signal processing.
 They are variously known as the Sherman–Morrison–Woodbury matrix inversion
 lemma, the Sherman–Morrison formula, and the Woodbury matrix identity.
 The fact that they are attributed to many authors is likely a reflection
 of the fact that they were discovered independently by a multitude of researche
rs at about the same time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Broadly speaking, they provide an affirmative answer to the following question:
 If, after computing the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

, we perturb it with a low rank (as opposed to a low magnitude) perturbation,
 can we efficiently compute the inverse of the perturbed matrix by perturbing
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 with a related low rank perturbation
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Proofs of these, and other related, identities can be found at 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woodbury_matrix_identity
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with the special case when the perturbation has rank 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 be an invertible 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 be column vectors of length 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (and hence of rank 1), and let 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 be any scalar.
 Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 below is not needed, as any such can be included in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 So I think we should just delete it.
 Don't delete it – it naturally generalizes to a matrix 
\series bold
C
\series default
 and makes clear the link to the Woodbury Matrix Identity
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mathbf{A}\,+\,c\,\mathbf{x}\,\mathbf{y}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}=\mathbf{A}^{-1}\,-\,\frac{c\,\mathbf{A}^{-1}\,\mathbf{x}\,\mathbf{y}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{A}^{-1}}{1\,+\,c\,\mathbf{x}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{A}^{-1}\mathbf{y}}.\label{eq:ShermanMorrison1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ShermanMorrison1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 simplifies even further when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}=\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n}$
\end_inset

, for in this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}^{-1}=\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

, and we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mathbf{I}_{n}\,+\,c\,\mathbf{x}\,\mathbf{y}^{\prime}\right)^{-1}=\mathbf{I}_{n}\,-\,\frac{c\mathbf{\,x}\,\mathbf{y}^{\prime}}{1\,+\,c\,\mathbf{x}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{y}}.\label{eq:ShermanMorrison2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ShermanMorrison1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ShermanMorrison2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be evaluated in 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(n^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 arithmetic operations (direct matrix inversion using Gaussian elimination
 requires 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(n^{3}\right)$
\end_inset

 operations), and even more importantly, they are numerically stable – small
 changes to any of the parameters on the left hand sides of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ShermanMorrison1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ShermanMorrison2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 result in small changes to their right hand sides.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I am planning to use this in Chapter example.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times k$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times n$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mathbf{A}\,+\,\mathbf{U\,\mathbf{C\mathbf{\,V}}}\right)^{-1}=\mathbf{A}^{-1}\,-\,\mathbf{A}^{-1}\,\mathbf{U}\left(\mathbf{C}^{-1}\,+\,\mathbf{V}\,\mathbf{A}^{-1}\,\mathbf{U}\right)^{-1}\,\mathbf{V}\,\mathbf{A}^{-1}\label{eq:Woodbury}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where it is assumed that the inverses all exist.
 Typically, 
\begin_inset Formula $k\ll n$
\end_inset

, making the inversion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}$
\end_inset

 far less tedious than direct recomputation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HendersonSearle1981"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hager1989"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provide a useful compendium of results related to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ShermanMorrison1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ShermanMorrison2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Woodbury"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, as well as a comprehensive summary of how they are applied in a variety
 of settings.
 One such result is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
a & b & \cdots & b\\
b & a & \cdots & b\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
b & b & \cdots & a
\end{array}\right]^{-1} & =\left[\left(a\,-\,b\right)\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n}\,+\,b\,\mathbf{1}_{n}\,\mathbf{1}_{n}^{\prime}\right]^{-1}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{a\,-\,b}\left[\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n}\,-\,\frac{b}{a\,+\,\left(n\,-\,1\right)\,b}\,\mathbf{J}_{n}\right].\label{eq:SingleFactorShermanMorrison}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{J}_{n}=\mathbf{1}_{n}\mathbf{1}_{n}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:AllOneMatrix"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and provided that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\,\ne\,b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\,+\,(n-1)\,b\ne0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result proves particularly useful when analyzing constant correlation
 matrices with 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\rho$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{-1\,}{\,\left(n-1\right)}<\rho<1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Outside this range, the matrix may be invertible, but it is not positive
 definite.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & \rho & \cdots & \rho\\
\rho & 1 & \cdots & \rho\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
\rho & \rho & \cdots & 1
\end{array}\right]^{-1} & =\frac{1}{1\,-\,\rho}\left[\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n}\,-\,\frac{\rho}{1\,+\,\left(n\,-\,1\right)\,\rho}\,\mathbf{J}_{n}\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\left(1\,+\,\left(n\,-\,1\right)\,\rho\right)\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n}\,-\,\rho\,\mathbf{J}_{n}}{\left(1\,-\,\rho\right)\left(1\,+\,\left(n\,-\,1\right)\,\rho\right)}.\label{eq:ConstantCorrelationShermanMorrison}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Inverse of a Covariance Matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometime, a closed form inverse of a matrix yields useful insights into
 the nature of its entries, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Stevens1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provides a particularly good example of this.
 Assume that we have a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 securities.
 The covariance matrix of their returns can be partitioned as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}_{n} & =\left[\begin{array}{c|c}
\mathrm{\sigma}_{1}^{2}\, & \,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{12}\\
\hline \mathbf{\Sigma}_{21}\, & \,\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}_{n\,-\,1}
\end{array}\right],\label{eq:GuyStevensCovMat}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the variance of security 1, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Sigma}_{12}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times(n-1)$
\end_inset

 vector that contains the covariances of security 1 with the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 securities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Sigma}_{21}=\mathbf{\Sigma}_{12}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}_{n\,-\,1}$
\end_inset

 is the covariance matrix of the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 securities.
 We can partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}_{n}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 in the same way we partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}_{n}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}_{n}^{-1}=\left[\begin{array}{c|c}
a_{11}\, & \,\mathbf{\Lambda}{}_{12}\\
\hline \mathrm{\mathbf{\Lambda}}_{21}\, & \,\mathrm{\mathbf{\Lambda}}_{22}
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:GuyStevensInverse1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}_{n}^{-1}\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}_{n} & =\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n},\nonumber \\
 & =\left[\begin{array}{c|c}
1\, & \,\mathbf{0}\\
\hline \mathbf{0}\, & \,\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n\,-\,1}
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:GuyStevensInverse2}
\end{align}

\end_inset

we can write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a_{11}\,\mathrm{\sigma}_{1}^{2}\,+\,\mathbf{\Lambda}_{12}\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{21} & =1\label{eq:GuyStevensInverse3}\\[0.5em]
a_{11}\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{12}\,+\,\mathbf{\Lambda}_{12}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}_{n-1} & =\mathbf{0}.\label{eq:GuyStevensInverse4}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On solving 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GuyStevensInverse4"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\Lambda}_{12}$
\end_inset

, substituting into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GuyStevensInverse3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and simplifying, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a_{11} & =\frac{1}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{1}^{2}\,-\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{12}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}_{n\,-\,1}^{-1}\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{21}}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{1}^{2}\,\left(1\,-\,R_{1}^{2}\right)}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{\epsilon}^{2}},\label{eq:GuyStevensA11}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the fraction of the variance of security 1 that is explained by securities
 
\begin_inset Formula $2,3,\cdots,n$
\end_inset

 when its returns are regressed against theirs, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\sigma}_{\epsilon}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the variance of the regression residuals.
 These are well known results in the theory of least squares, and are discussed
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Stevens1997"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hayashi2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Next, we write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{\Lambda}_{12} & =-a_{11}\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{12}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}_{n\,-\,1}^{-1}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{-\mathbf{\Sigma}_{12}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}_{n\,-\,1}^{-1}}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{1}^{2}\,\left(1\,-\,R_{1}^{2}\right)}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{-\mathrm{\boldsymbol{\beta}_{1}}}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{1}^{2}\,\left(1\,-\,R_{1}^{2}\right)},\label{eq:GuyStevensBeta1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\beta}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of regression coefficients obtained when security 1's returns
 are regressed against those of securities 
\begin_inset Formula $1,\cdots,\,i-1,\,i+1,\cdots,\,n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But since our choice of security 1 is arbitrary, all the rows must have
 exactly the same form, and the inverse of the covariance matrix must be
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}_{n}^{-1}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\frac{1}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{1}^{2}\left(1\,-\,R_{1}^{2}\right)}\, & \,\frac{-\beta_{12}}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{1}^{2}\left(1\,-\,R_{1}^{2}\right)}\, & \,\cdots\, & \,\frac{-\beta_{1n}}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{1}^{2}\left(1\,-\,R_{1}^{2}\right)}\\
\frac{-\beta_{21}}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{2}^{2}\left(1\,-\,R_{2}^{2}\right)}\, & \,\frac{1}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{2}^{2}\left(1\,-\,R_{2}^{2}\right)}\, &  & \,\frac{-\beta_{2n}}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{2}^{2}\left(1\,-\,R_{2}^{2}\right)}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \,\ddots\, & \vdots\\
\frac{-\beta_{n1}}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{n}^{2}\left(1\,-\,R_{n}^{2}\right)}\, & \,\frac{-\beta_{n2}}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{n}^{2}\left(1\,-\,R_{n}^{2}\right)}\, &  & \,\frac{1}{\mathrm{\sigma}_{n}^{2}\left(1\,-\,R_{n}^{2}\right)}
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:GuyStevensInverse5}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though we would not ever invert a covariance matrix in this way (both
 the data requirements and the computational effort are huge, and the procedure
 is not numerically stable), the insights it affords are valuable, and helps
 clarify our thinking about the structure of the inverse of a covariance
 matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Mahanalobis Distance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It sometimes proves useful to measure the distance between two random vectors
 that are drawn from the same 
\emph on
joint
\emph default
 distribution, but whose 
\emph on
marginal
\emph default
 distributions are very different.
 For example, vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{u}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 may contain the returns of all the stocks in the S&P 500 on two adjacent
 days, but the marginal distribution of their first entries (a volatile
 small cap biotech firm) may be very different than that of their last entry
 (a steadily growing consumer goods company).
 In such cases, it proves useful to first express the distance between each
 component of the two vectors in standard deviation units, and to then compute
 a standardized distance between them using a variant of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DistanceBetweenVectors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the special case when all the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{u}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

 are independent, this gives us
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{\mathrm{\mathbf{u}},\mathrm{\mathbf{v}}}=\sqrt{\left(\frac{u_{1}\,-\,v_{1}}{\sigma_{1}}\right)^{2}\,+\,\cdots\,+\,\left(\frac{u_{n}\,-\,v_{n}}{\sigma_{n}}\right)^{2}}.\label{eq:DistanceScaledBySigma}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, the 
\emph on
Mahalanobis distance
\emph default
 takes into account the covariances between the components of the vectors,
 and is defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{\mathrm{\mathbf{u}},\mathrm{\mathbf{v}}}^{M}=\sqrt{\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{u}}-\mathrm{\mathbf{v}}\right)^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{C}}^{-1}\,\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{u}}-\mathrm{\mathbf{v}}\right)},\label{eq:MahanalobisDistance}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is the covariance matrix of the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{u}}$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{v}}$
\end_inset

).
 If the covariance matrix is diagonal (i.e.
 if all the components of a vector are uncorrelated with each other), 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MahanalobisDistance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 reduces to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DistanceScaledBySigma"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Eigenvalues and Eigenvectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:AxEQb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 maps a non–zero vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

 to another vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{b}}$
\end_inset

 which may lie at a great distance from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

.
 But not all matrices push vectors far away: the identity matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n}$
\end_inset

, for example, maps every vector to itself, and a scalar multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n}$
\end_inset

 maps a vector to the same scalar multiple of itself.
 This property is not unique to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n}$
\end_inset

 – all square matrices map certain special vectors to scaled versions of
 themselves, i.e
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{A}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{e}}=\lambda\,\mathrm{\mathbf{e}}.}\label{eq:Eigenvector1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{e}}$
\end_inset

 is known as an 
\emph on
eigenvector
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

, the scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is its corresponding 
\emph on
eigenvalue
\emph default
, and they are collectively referred to as an 
\emph on
eigenpair
\emph default
.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{e}}$
\end_inset

 is not unique – any scalar multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{e}}$
\end_inset

 is also an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 Often, an eigenvector is scaled so that its norm is 1, and the resulting
 eigenvector is known as a 
\emph on
unit eigenvector
\emph default
 or a 
\emph on
normalized eigenvector
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we rewrite 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Eigenvector1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mathbf{A}\,-\,\lambda\,\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}\right)\mathrm{\mathbf{e}}=\mathrm{\mathbf{0},}\label{eq:Eigenvector2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 can be seen to be those values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}-\lambda\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}$
\end_inset

 is singular, or non–invertible, and therefore has a null space, or 
\emph on
eigenspace
\emph default
; any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

 that lies in the eigenspace associated with a particular eigenvalue is
 an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows from the definition of invertibility that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
det\left(\mathbf{A}\,-\,\lambda\,\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}\right)=0,\label{eq:Eigenenvector3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i},1\leqslant i\leqslant n$
\end_inset

 be an eigenvalue of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}\lambda_{i} & =\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}a_{ii}\nonumber \\
 & \triangleq trace\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}\right),\label{eq:SumOfEigenvalues}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\prod_{i\,=\,1}^{n}\lambda_{i}=det\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}\right).\label{eq:ProductOfEigenvalues}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of eigenvalues of a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 is known as its 
\emph on
spectrum
\emph default
, and its spectral radius, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(\mathbf{A}\right)$
\end_inset

, is defined to be 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho\left(\mathbf{A}\right)=\max_{i}\left|\lambda_{i}\right|,\label{eq:SpectralRadius1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and it can be shown that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho\left(\mathbf{A}\right)\leqslant\min\left(\max_{i}\sum_{j\,=\,1}^{n}\left|a_{ij}\right|,\ \max_{j}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}\left|a_{ij}\right|\right).\label{eq:SpectralRadius2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A few useful facts about the eigenpairs 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{e}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 follow:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is invertible, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nicefrac{1}{\lambda_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{e}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are an eigenpair of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}^{-1}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The eigenvalues (but not necessarily the eigenvectors) of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}^{\prime}}$
\end_inset

 are identical to the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}^{k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{e}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are an eigenpair of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}^{k},\ k>1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is triangular or diagonal, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}=a_{ii},\ 1\leqslant i\leqslant n$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}\,-\,k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{e}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are an eigenpair of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A\,-\,}k\,\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 is an invertible 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix, the eigenvalues (but not necessarily the eigenvectors) of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}^{-1}\,\mathbf{A}\,\mathbf{\mathbf{B}}$
\end_inset

 are identical to those of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 are distinct, or if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and has only real entries (covariance and correlation matrices
 are good examples of this second, weaker, condition), the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}$
\end_inset

 formed by stacking its normalized (i.e.
 of length 1) eigenvectors side by side diagonalizes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{P}^{-1}\,\mathbf{A}\,\mathbf{\mathbf{P}}=\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}\label{eq:EigenvaluesDiagonalizeA}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\lambda_{1} & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & \ddots &  & \vdots\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & 0\\
0 & \cdots & 0 & \lambda_{n}
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:Dlambda}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EigenvaluesDiagonalizeA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is often written as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{\mathbf{A}=\mathbf{P}\,\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}\,\mathbf{P}^{-1}},\label{eq:SpectralRepresentation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where it is called the 
\emph on
eigendecomposition
\emph default
, or the 
\emph on
spectral
\emph default
 
\emph on
representation
\emph default
, of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can further be shown that when the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 are distinct, or if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and has only real entries, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{P}^{-1}=\mathbf{P}^{\prime},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SpectralRepresentation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can usefully be rewritten as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{\mathbf{A}} & =\mathbf{P}\,\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}\,\mathbf{P}^{\prime}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\lambda_{i}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{p}}_{i}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{p}}_{i}^{\prime},\label{eq:SpectralRepresentation1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{p}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 column of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 is invertible only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is invertible, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 in turn is invertible if and only if all its eigenvalues are non–zero.
 Direct multiplication shows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}^{k} & =\mathbf{P}\,\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}^{k}\,\mathbf{P}^{-1}\nonumber \\
 & =\mathbf{P}\,\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}^{k}\,\mathbf{P}^{\prime}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}\lambda_{i}^{k}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{p}}_{i}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{p}}_{i}^{\prime},\ k\geqslant2,\label{eq:SpectralRepresentationOfPowers}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
under the above conditions, and it is also true that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\exp\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}\right) & =\mathbf{P}\,\exp\left(\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}\right)\,\mathbf{P}^{-1}\nonumber \\
 & =\mathbf{P}\,\exp\left(\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}\right)\,\mathbf{P}^{\prime},\label{eq:SpectralRepresentationOfExpA}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\exp\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}\right)\triangleq\mathbf{I}_{n}\,+\,\sum_{i\,>\,0}\frac{1}{i!}\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}^{i}\label{eq:MatrixExponential}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is known as the 
\emph on
matrix exponential
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\exp\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{0}}_{n}\right)=\mathbf{I}_{n}.\label{eq:MatrixExponential0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the special case when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 commute, i.e.
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\,\mathbf{B}=\mathbf{B}\,\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\exp\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}\right)\exp\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{B}}\right) & =\exp\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{B}}\right)\,\exp\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\exp\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}\,+\,\mathrm{\mathbf{B}}\right).\label{eq:MatrixExponentialProduct}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 commutes with itself, and as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}\,+}\,\left(-\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}\right)=\mathbf{0}_{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\exp\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}\right)^{-1}=\exp\left(-\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}\right).\label{eq:MatrixExponentialInverse}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EigenvaluesDiagonalizeA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be generalized: two matrices, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{B}}$
\end_inset

, are said to be 
\emph on
similar
\emph default
 if there exists an invertible matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{E}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{E}^{-1}\,\mathbf{A}\,\mathbf{\mathbf{E}}=\mathbf{B}.\label{eq:SimilarMatrices1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar matrices have identical eigenvalues, as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
det\left(\mathbf{B}\,-\,\lambda\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}\right) & =det\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{E}^{-1}}\left(\mathbf{A}\,-\,\lambda\,\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{E}}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =det\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{E}^{-1}}\right)det\left(\mathbf{A}\,-\,\lambda\,\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}\right)det\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{E}}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =det\left(\mathbf{A}\,-\,\lambda\,\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}\right).\label{eq:SimilarMatrices2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Positive Definite Matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\emph on
positive definite
\emph default
 if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{A\,x}}>\mathrm{\mathbf{0}}\ \forall\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\ne\mathrm{\mathbf{0}}.\label{eq:PositiveDefinite}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

An equivalent condition for positive definiteness is that all the eigenvalues
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 are strictly positive.
 If we relax the inequality slightly, i.e.
 if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{A\,x}}\geqslant\mathrm{\mathbf{0}}\ \forall\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\ne\mathrm{\mathbf{0}},\label{eq:PositiveSemiDefinite}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\emph on
positive semi–definite
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Negating each entry in a positive definitive (or positive semi–definite)
 matrix results in a 
\emph on
negative definite
\emph default
 (or 
\emph on
negative semi–definite
\emph default
) matrix – the inequalities in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PositiveDefinite"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PositiveSemiDefinite"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are reversed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Gramian matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}^{\prime}\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 is non–negative definite, as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{\mathbf{A}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{A}\,}x}} & =\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{A\,}x}\right)^{\prime}\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{A\,}x}\right)\nonumber \\
 & \geqslant\mathrm{\mathbf{0}\ \forall\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}}.\label{eq:GramianNonNegativeDefinite}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, the rank of the Gramian is identical to the rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is symmetric and positive semi–definite, its eigenvalues are non–negative.
 If it is symmetric and positive definite, its eigenvalues are strictly
 positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Positive definite matrices are of great importance in portfolio management
 because they are used to compute the variance of a portfolio from the variances
 and covariances of its constituent securities (the variance of a portfolio
 is, by definition, non–negative), and also find use when identifying extrema
 of multivariate functions
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Correspondingly, negative definite matrices find use when identifying maxima
 of multivariate functions.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a positive definite covariance matrix is symmetric and has only real
 entries, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EigenvaluesDiagonalizeA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

–
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SpectralRepresentation1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 apply, and we can write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{P}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{A}\,\mathbf{P}=\mathbf{D}_{\lambda},\label{eq:PDMatrixDiagonalization}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}$
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal matrix whose columns are the normalized eigenvalues of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix of eigenvalues – see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Dlambda"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 If we define
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}^{-1}}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\nicefrac{1}{\sqrt{\lambda_{1}}} & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & \ddots &  & \vdots\\
\vdots &  & \ddots & 0\\
0 & \cdots & 0 & \nicefrac{1}{\sqrt{\lambda_{n}}}
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:SqrtDlambdaInv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{Q}=\mathbf{P}\,\sqrt{\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}^{-1}},\label{eq:QFromP}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we can write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{Q}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{A}\,\mathbf{Q}=\mathbf{I}_{n}.\label{eq:CovarianceMatrixInverse}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using straightforward properties of Cholesky factorization and products
 of orthogonal matrices, it can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}$
\end_inset

 diagonalizes 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 positive definite covariance matrix, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{Q}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{B}\,\mathbf{Q}=\mathbf{D}_{1},\label{eq:PdiagonalizesB}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix, though its entries are not the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

.
 The matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 are said to be simultaneously diagonalizable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Itemize
Define eigenvalues and eigenvectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Spectral representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Positive definiteness 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Distribution of Eigenvalues?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Random Matrices?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Ignore these - too specialized, too hard
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
QR Decomposition and the Gram–Schmidt Procedure
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:QR_Decomposition"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that we have a set of vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{1},\,\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{2,}\,\cdots\,,\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{n}$
\end_inset

 which form an orthonormal basis
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
An orthogonal basis can be transformed into an orthonormal basis by dividing
 each vector by its norm.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

–dimensional vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{{S}}$
\end_inset

 .
 From the definition of orthonormality,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{i},\,\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{j}\right\rangle =\begin{cases}
1 & i=j\\
0 & i\ne j.
\end{cases}\label{eq:Orthonormality}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

–dimensional Euclidean space, we can stack them side by side to form an
 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}=\left[\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{1}\,\cdots\,\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{n}\right],\label{eq:Qmatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and it is easily seen that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}} & =\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n}.\label{eq:QtransposeQequalsIn}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can post–multiply both sides of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:QtransposeQequalsIn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 to obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}^{-1}=\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}^{\prime},\label{eq:QinverseEqualsQtranspose}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
but it is important to note that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:QtransposeQequalsIn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 (but not 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:QinverseEqualsQtranspose"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) holds even if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}$
\end_inset

 is rectangular, i.e.
 if the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are vectors in an 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

–dimensional Euclidean space, for 
\begin_inset Formula $m>n.$
\end_inset

 Also, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n}^{\prime}=\mathrm{\mathbf{I}}_{n}$
\end_inset

, it follows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}=\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}^{\prime}.\label{eq:QtransposeQ_2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remarkably, 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 matrix whose columns are linearly independent can be decomposed into a
 product of a orthonormal matrix and an invertible upper triangular matrix
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Normally, an upper triangular matrix would be represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{U}}$
\end_inset

, but it has become the norm to represent it in this particular factorization
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{R}}$
\end_inset

, possibly because all its entries lie to the right of the principal diagonal.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}=\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{R}}\label{eq:QRdecomposition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}$
\end_inset

 is orthonormal and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{R}}$
\end_inset

 is invertible and upper triangular.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
Gram–Schmidt
\emph default
 procedure is a constructive algorithm for creating 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}$
\end_inset

 from any full rank matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}=\left[\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}_{1}\,\cdots\,\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}_{n}\right].\label{eq:Amatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix of full rank.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we divide each column of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 by its norm, we get an equivalent
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Equivalent in the sense that the column space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is identical to the column space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}_{1}$
\end_inset

, whose columns all have norm 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}_{1} & =\left[\frac{\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}_{1}}{\left\Vert \mathrm{\mathbf{a}}_{1}\right\Vert }\,\cdots\,\frac{\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}_{n}}{\left\Vert \mathrm{\mathbf{a}}_{n}\right\Vert }\right]\nonumber \\
 & \triangleq\left[\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}_{1}^{1}\,\cdots\,\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}_{n}^{1}\right].\label{eq:A1matrix}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To construct 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}$
\end_inset

 using the Gram–Schmidt procedure, we first set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{1}=\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}_{1}^{1}$
\end_inset

, and then iteratively subtract the projections of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}_{i}^{1}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=2,\,3,\,\cdots\,,\,n$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{1},\,\cdots\,,\,\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{i-1}$
\end_inset

 from itself, and finally normalize the resulting vector to create a new
 vector that is orthonormal to all the preceding vectors.
 Formally,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{cl}
\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{1} & =\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}_{1}^{1}\\
\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{2} & =\frac{\mathbf{\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}}_{2}^{1}\,-\,\left\langle \mathbf{\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}}_{2}^{1},\,\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{1}\right\rangle \mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{1}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}}_{2}^{1}\,-\,\left\langle \mathbf{\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}}_{2}^{1},\,\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{1}\right\rangle \mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{1}\right\Vert }\\
 & \vdots\\
\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{n} & =\frac{\mathbf{\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}}_{n}^{1}\,-\,\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n\,-\,1}\left\langle \mathbf{\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}}_{n}^{1},\,\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{i}\right\rangle \mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{i}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}}_{n}^{1}\,-\,\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n\,-\,1}\left\langle \mathbf{\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}}_{n}^{1},\,\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{i}\right\rangle \mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{i}\right\Vert }
\end{array}\label{eq:GramSchmidt}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to check that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{q}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Orthonormality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and that the column space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}$
\end_inset

 is identical to the column space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 Keep in mind that the Gram–Schmidt procedure does not return a unique orthonorm
al matrix – if, for example, the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 are resequenced, it will return a different orthonormal matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though the Gram–Schmidt procedure makes clear the conceptual basis
 of orthonormalization, it is rarely used in practice on account of its
 numerically instability when the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 are almost collinear.
 And though its numerical stability can be improved by resequencing its
 computations (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Gentle2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for details), 
\emph on
Householder transformations
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
Givens rotations
\emph default
 are more widely used in practice to create 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{Q}}\mathbf{R}$
\end_inset

 decompositions, which see widespread use in the solution of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:AxEQb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fact that the transpose of an orthonormal matrix is its inverse leads
 to a subtly different notion of similarity: two matrices, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{B}}$
\end_inset

, are said to be 
\emph on
orthogonally similar
\emph default
 if there exists an orthonormal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{F}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{A\,}\mathbf{\mathbf{F}}=\mathbf{B}.\label{eq:SimilarMatrices3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 is upper triangular, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{F}\,\mathbf{B\,\mathbf{F}^{\prime}}$
\end_inset

is known as the 
\emph on
Schur factorization
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Singular Value Decomposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the special case when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is square and symmetric, it can be represented as the Gramian of some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 with rank 
\begin_inset Formula $r\leqslant\min\left(m,n\right)$
\end_inset

 (think of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 as time series of returns of securities, some of which may admit a riskless
 arbitrage), i.e.,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{\mathbf{A}}=\mathbf{B}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{B}.\label{eq:GramianOfPD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rank of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 is also 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, and it possesses a set of orthonormal eigenvectors that diagonalize it,
 i.e.
 its spectral representation is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{\mathbf{A}} & =\mathbf{Q}\,\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}\,\mathbf{Q}^{\prime},\label{eq:PDSpectralRepresentation}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Q}$
\end_inset

 is an orthonormal matrix whose columns are the normalized eigenvectors
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix whose entries are the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
Singular Value Decomposition
\emph default
 (SVD) generalizes and extends 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PDSpectralRepresentation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 matrices, and diagonalizes 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\mathbf{A}}_{n\times m}$
\end_inset

 using its 
\emph on
singular vectors
\emph default
 instead of its eigenvalues.
 The resulting decomposition represents any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix as a product of three matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{\mathbf{A}}_{n\,\times\,m}=\mathbf{U}_{n\,\times\,n}\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{n\,\times\,m}\,\mathbf{V}_{m\,\times\,m}^{\prime},\label{eq:SVD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}$
\end_inset

 are orthonormal matrices, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\mathbf{\Sigma}}$
\end_inset

 is diagonal in the following sense:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{ij}=\begin{cases}
\sigma_{i}>0 & 1\leqslant i=j\leqslant\mathrm{rank}\left(\mathbf{A}\right)\\
0 & \mathrm{otherwise}.
\end{cases}\label{eq:DiagMatrixInSVD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 are known as 
\emph on
singular values
\emph default
, and are the square roots of the non-zero eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

.
 Correspondingly, the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}$
\end_inset

 are the orthonormal eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\,\mathbf{A}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 and those of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}$
\end_inset

 are the orthonormal eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

.
 They are known as the 
\emph on
left
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
right singular vectors
\emph default
, respectively, of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

.
 For symmetric, square, matrices, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SVD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 reduces to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PDSpectralRepresentation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recognizing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}^{-1}=\mathbf{V}^{\prime},$
\end_inset

we can rewrite 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SVD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{\mathbf{A}}_{n\,\times\,m}\,\mathbf{V}_{m\,\times\,m}=\mathbf{U}_{n\,\times\,n}\,\mathbf{\Sigma}_{n\,\times\,m},\label{eq:SVD1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 maps the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}$
\end_inset

 to scaled versions of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}$
\end_inset

.
 Addtionally, we can partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}$
\end_inset

 into two adjacent block matrices 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{U} & =\left[\mathrm{\mathbf{U}}_{1}\ |\ \mathrm{\mathbf{U}}_{2}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\mathrm{\mathbf{u}}_{1} & \,\cdots & \ \mathrm{\mathbf{u}}_{r}\ |\ \mathrm{\mathbf{u}}_{r+1}\,\cdots\ \mathrm{\mathbf{u}}_{n}\end{array}\right]\label{eq:SVDu}\\[0.5em]
\mathbf{V} & =\left[\mathrm{\mathbf{V}}_{1}\ |\ \mathrm{\mathbf{V}}_{2}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\mathrm{\mathbf{v}}_{1} & \,\cdots & \ \mathrm{\mathbf{v}}_{r}\ |\ \mathrm{\mathbf{v}}_{r+1}\,\cdots\ \mathrm{\mathbf{v}}_{m}\end{array}\right],\label{eq:SVDv}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and it can be shown that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cl}
\mathbf{U}_{1} & =\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\mathrm{\mathbf{u}}_{1} & \,\cdots\  & \mathrm{\mathbf{u}}_{r}\end{array}\right]\hspace{0.315cm}\mathrm{is\ an\ orthonormal\boldsymbol{\ }basis\ for\ the\ \mathit{\mathit{column}\ space}\ of\ \mathbf{\mathbf{A}}}\\
\mathbf{U}_{2} & =\left[\mathrm{\mathbf{u}}_{r\,+\,1}\,\cdots\ \mathrm{\mathbf{u}}_{n}\right]\hspace{0.12cm}\mathrm{is\ an\ orthonormal\boldsymbol{\ }basis\ for\ \mathbf{\mathcal{{N}}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}^{\prime}\right)},\ the\ \mathit{left\ null\ space}\ of}\ \mathrm{\mathbf{A}}\\
\mathbf{V}_{1} & =\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\mathrm{\mathbf{v}}_{1} & \,\cdots\  & \mathrm{\mathbf{v}}_{r}\end{array}\right]\hspace{0.335cm}\mathrm{is\ an\ orthonormal\boldsymbol{\ }basis\ for\ the}\ row\ \mathit{space}\ \mathrm{of}\ \mathbf{\mathbf{A}}\\
\mathbf{V}_{2} & =\left[\mathrm{\mathbf{v}}_{r\,+\,1}\,\cdots\ \mathrm{\mathbf{v}}_{m}\right]\ \mathrm{is\ an\ orthonormal\boldsymbol{\ }basis\ for\ \mathbf{\mathcal{{N}}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}\right)},\ the}\ \mathit{null\ space}\ \mathrm{of}\ \mathbf{A}.
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we write out 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SVD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 in terms of the left and right singular vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{u}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{v}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}_{1}$
\end_inset

 (the orthonormal bases for its column space and row space respectively),
 we see that the SVD allows us to represent
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 as a sum of rank 1 matrices:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{\mathbf{A}}=\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{r}\sigma_{i}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{u}}_{i}\,\mathbf{v}_{i}^{\prime}.\label{eq:SVD2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we further reorder the terms on the right hand side of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SVD2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 in descending order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

, we obtain a decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 in which the terms are ranked in descending order of importance, and we
 can obtain a sequence of increasingly accurate approximations to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 by computing the partial sums of the first 
\begin_inset Formula $p<r$
\end_inset

 terms of this reordered sequence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is, in fact, the way in which the SVD is most often used – a small,
 but important, subset of the terms in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SVD2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is used to construct an adequate approximation to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{A}}$
\end_inset

 that greatly simplifies computations using it.
 In many real life applications, matrices with many millions of entries
 are well approximated by a partial sum with ten or twenty terms, speeding
 up computations by many orders of magnitude.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Some Results on Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Derivatives of Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 be a differentiable function of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\,x_{2},\cdots\,,\,x_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\emph on
gradient
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right),\ \nabla f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

, is a vector of its partial derivatives, and is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\partial f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{1}}\\
\vdots\\
\frac{\partial f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{n}}
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:GradientFx}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The gradient vector points in the direction in which 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

's rate of change is maximal.
 In the special case when 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right) & =\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}a_{i}\,x_{i}\nonumber \\
 & =\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}\cdotp\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\label{eq:fx_dot_product}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
it is easily seen that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)=\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}.\label{eq:GradientDotProduct}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
quadratic form
\emph default
, i.e.
 if
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right) & =\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}\sum_{j\,=\,1}^{n}a_{ij}\,x_{i}\,x_{j}\nonumber \\
 & =\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{A}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\label{eq:fx_quadratic_form}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}$
\end_inset

 are constants, it can be seen by differentiating and gathering terms that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)=2\,\mathbf{A}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}.\label{eq:GradientQuadraticForm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 is twice differentiable, its Hessian, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{H}}\left(f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

, is a symmetric square matrix of its second partial derivatives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathrm{\mathbf{H}}\left(f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)\right) & =\frac{\partial^{2}f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\partial\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}^{\prime}}\nonumber \\
 & =\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\frac{\partial^{2}f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{1}^{2}}\, & \,\frac{\partial^{2}f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{1}\,\partial x_{2}}\, & \cdots & \,\frac{\partial^{2}f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{1}\,\partial x_{n}}\\
\frac{\partial^{2}f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{2}\,\partial x_{1}}\, & \,\frac{\partial^{2}f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{2}^{2}}\, & \cdots & \,\frac{\partial^{2}f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{2}\,\partial x_{n}}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
\frac{\partial^{2}f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{n}\,\partial x_{1}}\, & \,\frac{\partial^{2}f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{n}\,\partial x_{2}}\, & \cdots & \,\frac{\partial^{2}f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{n}^{2}}
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:Hessian}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Hessian matrix reflects the magnitude, as well as the principal axes,
 of the local curvature of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{g}}\left(x\right)=\left[\begin{array}{c}
g_{1}\left(x\right)\\
\vdots\\
g_{n}\left(x\right)
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:VectorOfFunctions}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is a vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

–times differentiable functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}\left(x\right),\,g_{2}\left(x\right),\,\cdots\,,\,g_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, of a single variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, then 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d^{k}\mathrm{\mathbf{g}}\left(x\right)}{dx^{k}}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\frac{d^{k}g_{1}\left(x\right)}{dx^{k}}\\
\vdots\\
\frac{d^{k}g_{n}\left(x\right)}{dx^{k}}
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:VectorOfDerivatives}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:VectorOfDerivatives"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 generalizes naturally to matrices.
 If 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{G}}\left(x\right)=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
g_{11}\left(x\right) & \,\cdots\, & g_{1m}\left(x\right)\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots\\
g_{n1}\left(x\right) & \,\cdots\, & g_{nm}\left(x\right)
\end{array}\right]\label{eq:MatrixOfFunctions}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is a matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

–times differentiable functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{11}\left(x\right),\,\cdots\,,\,g_{nm}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

, of a single variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d^{k}\mathrm{\mathbf{G}}\left(x\right)}{dx^{k}}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{d^{k}g_{11}\left(x\right)}{dx^{k}} & \,\cdots\, & \frac{dg_{1m}^{k}\left(x\right)}{dx^{k}}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots\\
\frac{d^{k}g_{n1}\left(x\right)}{dx^{k}} & \,\cdots\, & \frac{d^{k}g_{nm}\left(x\right)}{dx^{k}}
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:MatrixOfDerivatives}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Taylor Series
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taylor series provide a way in which to approximate infinitely differentiable
 functions around a point.
 The Taylor series of an infinitely differentiable function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 of a single variable around a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(x\right) & =f\left(x_{0}\right)+\sum_{i\,\geqslant\,1}\left.\frac{1}{i!}\left(x\,-\,x_{0}\right)^{i}\frac{d^{i}f\left(x\right)}{dx^{i}}\right|_{x\,=\,x_{0}}\nonumber \\
 & =f\left(x_{0}\right)+\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{k}\left.\frac{1}{i!}\left(x\,-\,x_{0}\right)^{i}\frac{d^{i}f\left(x\right)}{dx^{i}}\right|_{x\,=\,x_{0}}+r_{k\,+\,1}(x),\label{eq:UnivariateTaylorSeries}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{k+1}(x)$
\end_inset

 is a remainder term.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Often, we assume that the remainder term can be ignored, focus on just the
 first three terms of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:UnivariateTaylorSeries"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(x\right)\approx f\left(x_{0}\right)+\left(x\,-\,x_{0}\right)\left.\frac{df\left(x\right)}{dx}\right|_{x\,=\,x_{0}}+\frac{1}{2}\left(x\,-\,x_{0}\right)^{2}\left.\frac{d^{2}f\left(x\right)}{dx^{2}}\right|_{x\,=\,x_{0}}.\label{eq:TwoTermUnivariateTaylorSeries}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While a multivariate extension of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:UnivariateTaylorSeries"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 exists, it is a three term expansion, analogous to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TwoTermUnivariateTaylorSeries"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, that finds the most use in portfolio construction and risk management:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)\approx f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{0}\right)+\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\,-\,\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{0}\right)\left.\nabla f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)\right|_{\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}=\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{0}}+\frac{1}{2}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\,-\,\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{0}\right)^{\prime}\left.\mathrm{\mathbf{H}}\left(f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)\right)\right|_{x=x_{0}}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\,-\,\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{0}\right).\label{eq:TwoTermMultivariateTaylorSeries}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to keep in mind that a Taylor series expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
local
\emph default
 expansion, and is typically valid only in a small region centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{0}$
\end_inset

 changes, so does its Taylor series, as well as its gradient and its Hessian.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Convex and Concave Functions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:ConvexFunctions"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 of single variable is 
\emph on
concave
\emph default
 if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f((1\,-\,\alpha)\,x\,+\,\alpha\,y)\geqslant(1\,-\,\alpha)\,f(x)\,+\,\alpha\,f(y).\label{eq:ConcaveFunction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
strictly concave
\emph default
 if the strict inequality 
\begin_inset Formula $f((1\,-\,\alpha)\,x\,+\,\alpha\,y)>(1\,-\,\alpha)\,f(x)\,+\,\alpha\,f(y)$
\end_inset

 holds for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\ne y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A differentiable function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is (strictly) concave on an interval if and only if its derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}(x)$
\end_inset

 is (strictly) monotonically decreasing on that interval.
 If a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a second derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime\prime}(x)$
\end_inset

 on an interval, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is (strictly) concave if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime\prime}(x)$
\end_inset

 is (negative) non–positive on that interval.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is concave and differentiable, then it is bounded above by its first–order
 Taylor approximation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x)\leqslant f(x_{0})\,+\,f^{\prime}(x_{0})\,\cdot\,(x\,-\,x_{0})\ \forall x,\,x_{0},\label{eq:ConcaveFunctionUpperBound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and has a global 
\emph on
maximum
\emph default
 that is achieved at one of the two boundaries of the interval or at a point
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}(x_{0})=0.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 of single variable is 
\emph on
convex
\emph default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $-f(x)$
\end_inset

 is concave, i.e.
 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

,  
\begin_inset Formula $f((1\,-\,\alpha)\,x\,+\,\alpha\,y)\leqslant(1\,-\,\alpha)\,f(x)\,+\,\alpha\,f(y)$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
strictly convex
\emph default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f((1\,-\,\alpha)\,x\,+\,\alpha\,y)<(1\,-\,\alpha)\,f(x)\,+\,\alpha\,f(y)\ \forall\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
and 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula $x\ne y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A differentiable function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is (strictly) convex on an interval if and only if its derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}(x)$
\end_inset

 is (strictly) monotonically increasing on that interval.
 If a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 has a second derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime\prime}(x)$
\end_inset

 on an interval then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is (strictly) convex if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime\prime}(x)$
\end_inset

 is (positive) non–negative on that interval.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is convex and differentiable, it is bounded below by its first-order Taylor
 approximation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x)\geqslant f(x_{0})\,+\,f^{\prime}(x_{0})\cdot(x\,-\,x_{0})\ \forall\,x,\,x_{0},\label{eq:ConvexFunctionLowerBound}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and has a global 
\emph on
minimum
\emph default
 that is achieved at one of the two boundaries of the interval or at a point
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}(x_{0})=0.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Jensen's inequality
\emph default
, which sees extensive use in continuous time finance, concerns the expected
 value of convex and concave functions of a random variable, states that
 for any random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

, and for any convex function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left[f\left(Z\right)\right]\geqslant f\left(E\left[Z\right]\right).\label{eq:JensensInequalityConvexFunction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is concave, the direction of the inequality is reversed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Jensen's inequality is easily seen to be true by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}=E\left[Z\right]$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConcaveFunctionUpperBound"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConvexFunctionLowerBound"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and then taking the expectation of both sides.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Multivariate Convex and Concave Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To extend the notions of convexity and concavity to functions of many variables,
 we need to define a 
\emph on
convex set
\emph default
.
 A set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is said to be convex if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}\in S$
\end_inset

, the line segment joining 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}$
\end_inset

 lies within, or on the boundary of, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
(1\,-\,\alpha)\,\mathbf{x}\,+\,\alpha\,\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}\in S.\label{Convex set}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A multivariable function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 that is defined on a convex set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is said to be concave if it satisfies 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ConcaveFunction"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with the scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 being replaced by vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}$
\end_inset

.
 Replacing scalars with vectors allows us to similarly define strictly concave,
 convex and strictly convex functions by analogy to their definitions in
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "subsec:ConvexFunctions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A twice–differentiable function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 is convex (strictly convex) if its Hessian, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{H}}\left(f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

, is positive semi–definite (positive definite), and concave (strictly concave)
 if its Hessian is negative semi–definite (negative definite).
 Intuitively, a strictly convex function must lie above, and a strictly
 concave function must lie below, a hyperplane that is tangent to its surface
 at any point 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TwoTermMultivariateTaylorSeries"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 makes clear that this can only be guaranteed for sufficiently small 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\,-\,\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{0}$
\end_inset

 if the Hessian is positive definite (for convex functions) or negative
 definite (for concave functions).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Euler's Theorem for Homogeneous Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 is said to be homogeneous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $𝑘>0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(c\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)=c^{k}f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)\ \forall c>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Euler’s theorem for homogeneous functions states that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 is homogeneous of degree 
\begin_inset Formula $𝑘$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)=\frac{1}{k}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{n}x_{i}\,\frac{\partial f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{i}}.\label{eq:EulersTheorem1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By way of example, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)=x_{1}^{2}\,+\,x_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is homogenous of degree 2 because
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(c\,\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right) & =c^{2}\left(x_{1}^{2}\,+\,x_{2}^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =c^{2}f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)\label{eq:EulersTheorem2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and it is easily seen that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right) & =\frac{1}{2}\left(x_{1}\cdotp2x_{1}\,+\,x_{2}\cdotp2x_{2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\left(x_{1}\frac{\partial f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{1}}\,+\,x_{2}\frac{\partial f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)}{\partial x_{2}}\right).\label{eq:EulersTheorem3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The General Problem of Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A very general statement of an optimization problem is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\mathrm{maximize}\ \  & f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)\\
\mathrm{subject\ to}\\
g\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right) & \geqslant0\\
h\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right) & =\mathrm{\mathbf{b}}\\
\mathrm{\mathbf{x}} & \in S.
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:GeneralOptimizationProblem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This problem is virtually limitless in both its scope and its difficulty:
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right),\ g\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 may be both nonlinear and discontinuous in their arguments, and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 may be bounded, non–convex, finite or countable (e.g.
 some or all the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}$
\end_inset

 may be restricted to be integers); 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 may have multiple local maxima that are not easily distinguished from its
 global maximum, and its evaluation may be numerically unstable and computationa
lly demanding.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We therefore focus here only on the optimization of sufficiently smooth
 (i.e.
 twice differentiable) concave (or convex) functions defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 with linear equality constraints.
 Fortunately, this covers many of the problems that actually arise in portfolio
 management.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Optimizing Twice–Differentiable Convex Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Twice–differentiable convex (concave) functions with positive (negative)
 definite Hessians play a central role in portfolio construction as they
 are easily optimized when 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, the convex set on which they are defined, is unbounded.
 Any extremum of such a function must necessarily be a minimum or a maximum,
 depending on whether the Hessian is positive or negative definite.
 The sole condition for an extremum is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{opt}\right)=\mathbf{0},\label{eq:GradientFxEq0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GradientFx"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{H}}\left(f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 is positive (negative) definite, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is minimized (maximized) at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{opt}$
\end_inset

.
 Intuitively, this follows from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:TwoTermMultivariateTaylorSeries"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

: as the gradient is 0 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{opt}$
\end_inset

, the linear term disappears, and only the quadratic term survives, so that
 the function must increase (decrease) as one moves away from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}_{opt}$
\end_inset

 in any direction according to whether 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{H}}\left(f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 is positive (negative) definite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Method of Lagrange Multipliers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We next extend our technique for optimizing twice–differentiable convex
 (concave) functions with positive (negative) definite Hessians to permit
 the inclusion of a single linear equality constraint of the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{a^{\prime}\,x}}=b\mathrm{,}\label{eq:EqualityConstraints}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{a}}$
\end_inset

 is a vector with constant real entries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method of 
\emph on
Lagrange multipliers,
\emph default
 which maps a constrained optimization to a related unconstrained optimization,
 is a powerful technique for solving problems such as this.
 It starts by constructing a new function, the 
\emph on
Lagrangian
\emph default
, that combines the function and the linear constraint:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\,\theta\right)=f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)\,-\,\theta\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{a^{\prime}\,x}}\,-\,b\right).\label{eq:Lagrangian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is known as a Lagrange multiplier, and at a stationary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\mathcal{L}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\,\theta\right)=\mathbf{0},\label{eq:GradientLagrangianEq0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\mathcal{L}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\,\theta\right)=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\,\theta\right)}{\partial x_{1}}\\
\vdots\\
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\,\theta\right)}{\partial x_{n}}\\
\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\,\theta\right)}{\partial\theta}
\end{array}\right].\label{eq:GradientLagrangianDefinition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equality constraint 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EqualityConstraints"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 must be satisfied at any stationary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, as, if it is not, we can increase the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 by choosing a different value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, contradicting our assumption that it is a stationary point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observe that for any fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, the Hessian of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 is identical to that of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

, as differentiating 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 twice with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 fixed eliminates all the terms contributed by the linear constraint.
 In particular, if the Hessian of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 is positive (negative) definite, so is that of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that if the Hessian of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 is negative definite, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 achieves its constrained maximum at a stationary point of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{x}},\,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An identical argument allows for the constrained minimization of functions
 with positive definite Hessians, and this technique is easily extended
 to multiple linear equality constraints – we need only add one Lagrange
 multiplier per constraint, and ensure that the derivative of the Lagrangian
 with respect to each Lagrange multiplier is 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once we allow for the inclusion of inequality constraints or non–linear
 (typically quadratic) constraints, the optimization problem becomes much
 harder, and we refer the reader to specialized textbooks on optimization
 such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "LuenbergerYe2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "CornuejolsEtAl2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kwan2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kwan2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "MarkowitzStarerFramGerber2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provide useful expositions of optimization models that are of particular
 relevance to portfolio management, along with Python and R code, as well
 as Excel spreadsheets, to assist in their implementation.
\end_layout

